Heat a #frying pan{} on medium-high heat and add the @lamb mince{200%g}. Use a
#wooden spoon{} to break it up. Cook until browned, ~{8-10%minutes}.

Halve, peel and thinly slice the @red onion{1}(peeled and thinly sliced) into
half moons. Halve, then remove the core from the @bell pepper{1}(core removed)
and thinly slice. Peel and grate the @ginger{1/2%piece}(peeled and grated).
Drain the @chickpeas{1%400g can} in a #colander{} and rinse them under cold water.

Pop the @basmati rice{150%g} and @star anise{1/2} in a large #saucepan{}. Pour in
the @water for the rice{300%ml}, add a pinch of @salt{pinch} and put the pan on
high heat. Once boiling, reduce the heat to medium and cover with a #lid{}
(or some foil). Cook for ~{10%minutes}. Then remove from the heat (with the lid
still on) and set aside for another ~{10%minutes}.

> TIP: The rice will continue to cook in its own steam.

When the lamb has browned, add the @mustard seeds{1%tsp}, onion and pepper.
Cook for ~{5%minutes}. Add the @Sri Lankan style curry powder{1} and ginger.
Cook for ~{1%minute} more. Add the chickpeas and @tomato passata{1}(400g can).
Bring to the boil. Lastly add the @chicken stock powder{1/2%tsp} and
@water for the curry{200%ml}. Lower the heat and simmer gently until the liquid
has reduced by half, ~{10-15%minutes}.

Meanwhile, roughly chop the @coriander{1}(roughly chopped, stalks and all). When
the curry has been bubbling away for ~{5%minutes}, stir in the
@courgette{1}(chopped) and cook until the greens have softened and the sauce has
thickened, another ~{5-7%minutes}. Remove from the heat. Taste the sauce and
add @salt and @pepper if necessary. Stir in half the coriander.

Take the lid off the rice, remove the star anise and fluff up with a #fork{}.
Spoon the rice onto #plates{} and serve your lamb and chickpea curry on top.
Finish with a sprinkle of coriander. Enjoy!